docs.abstract: Auto companies lined up to protest potential tariffs on $351 billion in automobiles and parts at a hearing in Washington on Thursday.
docs.snippet: Auto companies lined up to protest potential tariffs on $351 billion in automobiles and parts at a hearing in Washington on Thursday.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Richard Smallwood describes himself as a “pretty far right-wing conservative” and a longtime supporter of President Trump. But like many in the auto industry, Mr. Smallwood, the president of the tire company Sumitomo Rubber North America, has been puzzled and dismayed by the president’s proposal to impose tariffs on foreign automobiles and their parts.

headline.main: On Trump’s Car Tariffs, Companies Are United in Dissent
headline.print_headline: Auto Companies United In Warning That Tariffs Could Hurt U.S. Industry

docs.abstract: The Trump administration has begun granting a handful of exclusions from its steel and aluminum tariffs, but the slow, opaque process still has nearly 20,000 applications waiting.
docs.snippet: The Trump administration has begun granting a handful of exclusions from its steel and aluminum tariffs, but the slow, opaque process still has nearly 20,000 applications waiting.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration granted seven companies the first set of exclusions from its metal tariffs this week and rejected requests from 11 other companies, as the Commerce Department began slowly responding to the 20,000 applications that companies have filed for individual products.

headline.main: Companies Get First Tariff Waivers, but Many More Are Left in Limbo
headline.print_headline: Firms Get First Tariff Waivers, but Many More Are in Limbo

docs.abstract: The Office of Government Ethics warned that the commerce secretary’s failure to make required divestitures could have placed him in a position to violate conflict of interest laws.
docs.snippet: The Office of Government Ethics warned that the commerce secretary’s failure to make required divestitures could have placed him in a position to violate conflict of interest laws.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Wilbur Ross, the commerce secretary, said he would sell all of his remaining stock holdings after the Office of Government Ethics faulted him for continuing to maintain investments that he was required to divest and entering into new ones.

headline.main: Wilbur Ross Says He Will Sell Stock After Watchdog Warns of Potential for Criminal Violation
